# isolation_allowed.rc — ALLOWED process patterns for isolation_report.sh
#
# Threads matching these patterns are ALLOWED on isolated cores.
# These are kernel housekeeping threads that may briefly appear even
# on well-isolated cores.  They are reported but not flagged as
# violations.  High switch counts here may indicate incomplete
# isolation (missing nohz_full=, rcu_nocbs=, etc.).
#
# FORMAT:
#   One bash-extended-regex pattern per line, matched against the
#   thread's "comm" field (the 16-char kernel task name).
#   Lines starting with '#' and blank lines are ignored.
#
# REGEX QUICK REFERENCE (bash =~ extended regex):
#   ^           match start of string
#   $           match end of string
#   .           any single character
#   *           zero or more of the previous
#   +           one or more of the previous
#   ?           zero or one of the previous
#   [abc]       character class (a, b, or c)
#   [^abc]      negated class (not a, b, or c)
#   (a|b)       alternation (a or b)
#   \.  \-      literal dot / hyphen (escape special chars)
#
# EXAMPLES:
#   ^cpuhp/           match CPU hotplug threads
#   ^posixcputmr/     match POSIX CPU timer threads

# --- Kernel scheduling / migration ---
^migration/
^watchdog/

# --- Softirq / workqueue ---
^ksoftirqd/
^kworker/

# --- IRQ threads ---
^irq/

# --- RCU ---
^rcuc/
^rcub/

# --- Memory management ---
^kcompactd
